  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering at both the international and national levels. Here are some key examples:\n\n### International Framework\n1. **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This is one of the first international treaties to criminalize money laundering, particularly in relation to drug trafficking.\n2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**: The FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Its 40 Recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n### United States\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**: Requires financial institutions to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering by maintaining records and filing reports that could be useful in criminal, tax, or regulatory investigations.\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**: Makes money laundering a federal crime and requires financial institutions to report cash transactions over $10,000.\n3. **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001**: Expands the BSA to include additional measures to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### European Union\n1. **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**: The EU has issued several directives to combat money laundering and terrorist financing, with the latest being the 6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD6) in 2018.\n\n### United Kingdom\n1. **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)**: Criminalizes money laundering and provides for the recovery of the proceeds of crime.\n\n### Canada\n1. **Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act (PCMLTFA)**: Establishes the framework for detecting and deterring money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### Australia\n1. **Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorism Financing Act 2006 (AML/CTF Act)**: Provides the legislative framework to detect and deter money laundering and terrorism financing.\n\n### Other Countries\nMost countries have enacted their own laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in line with international standards set by bodies like the FATF.\n\nThese statutes typically include provisions for:\n- Criminalizing the act of money laundering.\n- Requiring financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs.\n- Mandating the reporting of suspicious transactions.\n- Imposing penalties for non-compliance, including fines and imprisonment.\n\nThe specifics can vary widely from one jurisdiction to another, but the overarching goal is to prevent the illegal activities that generate the proceeds being laundered and to punish those involved in the laundering process.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
